   Saxon Documentation Saxonica ▷ Saxon ▷ About Saxon ▷ Getting Started ▷ Getting started with Saxon on the Java platform About Saxon Getting Started Getting started with Saxon on the Java platform Getting started with Saxon on the .NET platform What is Saxon? Choosing the Saxon Edition Installation: Java platform Installation: .NET platform Saxon Licenses Source code, samples, and other resources Historical Note Technical Support Related Products Change History Licensing Configuration Handling XML Documents Using XSLT Using XQuery Using XPath Using XML Schema (XSD) The Gizmo Utility Saxon on .NET Extensibility Mechanisms Saxon Extensions Sample Saxon Applications Saxon SQL Extension Reference: XSLT Elements Reference: XPath Syntax Reference: Function Library Standards Conformance Using this Documentation Getting started with Saxon on the Java platform Saxon doesn't come with a graphical user interface: it's designed to be integrated into other tools and applications. You will therefore start by using it from the operating system command line. On Windows, you may want to install a text editor such as jEdit that offers a more friendly command line than the standard DOS console provided by Microsoft. Alternatively, Saxon is integrated with popular XML development environments such as Oxygen XML Editor and Stylus Studio , which will handle all the installation dependencies. Ensure that Java is installed. Saxon 10 requires Java 8 or later. If for some reason you need to run with an
  
