  URL https://www.saxonica.com/html/documentation10/using-xsl/embedding/s9api-transformation.html
   Saxon Documentation Saxonica ▷ Saxon ▷ Using XSLT ▷ Invoking XSLT from an application ▷ Using s9api for Transformations About Saxon Change History Licensing Configuration Handling XML Documents Using XSLT Running XSLT from the Command Line Running Saxon XSLT Transformations from Ant Invoking XSLT from an application Using s9api for Transformations Using JAXP for Transformations Compiling a Stylesheet Performance Analysis XSLT 3.0 Support Using XQuery Using XPath Using XML Schema (XSD) The Gizmo Utility Saxon on .NET Extensibility Mechanisms Saxon Extensions Sample Saxon Applications Saxon SQL Extension Reference: XSLT Elements Reference: XPath Syntax Reference: Function Library Standards Conformance Using this Documentation Using s9api for Transformations You can perform a transformation using the s9api interface as follows: Create a Processor and set any global configuration options on the Processor . If your stylesheet uses any features that require Saxon-PE or Saxon-EE, be sure to use the constructor new Processor(true) . Call newXsltCompiler() to create an XsltCompiler , and set any options that are local to a specific compilation (for example, the destination of error messages). By default, error messages are directed to the System.err output stream, which is fine for an application run from a console, but not so good if it's executing on a web server, or behind a graphical interface. In such cases you'll want to think carefully about where to direct the error messages. One mechanism that is often convenient is to call XsltCompiler.setErrorList() supplying a List into which Saxon will place the error messages; on completion the application can examine the list and display the errors to the user in whatever way is most suitable. Call the compile() method to compile a stylesheet. The result is an XsltExecutable , which can be used as often as you like, in the same thread or in different threads. To run a transformation, call either the load() or load30() method 
  
